article.headline: Jackson posts second career triple-double
article.linkText: Jackson's triple-double sends No. 5 Ducks past Florida A&M
article.story:
EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Luke Jackson had his second career triple-double with 14 points, 11 rebounds and 10 assists as No. 5 Oregon bounced back with a 107-66 romp over Florida A&M on Friday night.

It was only the third triple-double in Ducks history. Ron Lee had the first in 1972 and Jackson had the second in 2001.

Luke Ridnour added 21 points for Oregon (7-1), which won its 21st consecutive game at home, the fifth-longest streak in the country and second-longest in Ducks' history.

On Tuesday night, Oregon lost to unranked Cincinnati 77-52 at East Rutherford, N.J., in the Jimmy V Classic.

   Jermaine Hill led the Rattlers (3-4) with 17 points and 10
rebounds. Terrence Woods added 11 points and six boards for the
Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference team, which was playing a Pac-10
opponent for the first time.

After a competitive opening nine minutes, the Ducks pulled away
from an 18-16 game with a 16-2 run.
	
Keyed by a relentless pressure defense, Oregon got transition opportunities and quick looks inside off the halfcourt set to break the Rattlers' spirit.

By halftime, the Ducks had a 22-point lead and the focus was on Sunday's matchup with No. 25 Minnesota. The Gophers defeated Oregon 75-72 last year.

Oregon opened the second half with a 23-5 run.

The Ducks had six players in double-figures and tied a school
record with 30 assists. Five players had at least four assists.

Ian Crosswhite scored 18 points for Oregon. Robert Johnson had 13 points and eight rebounds, James Davis had 16 points and Andre Joseph had 13.

Oregon broke 100 points for the second time in three games.
